text: It's probably a combination of all four, but if we had to choose one, I'd go with analytical. All the data we have is publicly available. Anyone can go to the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office website and download the patents. Anyone can go to Glassdoor and read reviews on various employers. The challenge really is just processing this huge amount of information. The data is quite large. It requires a significant investment in technological infrastructure to extract, store, and to process. The bigger challenge, even from there, I think, is just making sense of all of it. Look, if you were to take the thousands of words in, say, a 10K and throw them into a linear regression, you would get nothing useful. Investors need to use specialized natural language processing, NLP, models in order to derive meaningful insights from this sort of data. But even with these tools, you can't simply brute force it. Unstructured data is super high-dimensional. So, again, a single 10K can have thousands of unique words. Simply trying to data mine. To find the patterns that, say, correlate with future returns. That doesn't work. Instead, analysts need to use their fundamental intuition to guide their exploration of the data. So, for example, you know, we might have a hunch that the use of swear words in earnings call is a bad sign. To test this is actually very simple. The challenge, of course, was knowing where to look in the first place. Using intuition to guide us allows us to significantly narrow down the search space so that it becomes tractable for our models. So, again, I guess the edge here. Is that the analytical analysis requires the intersection of two skill sets. Machine learning and investment intuition. Both are, you know, at least to some degree, uncommon. And the combination, of course, being, you know, even less prevalent.
